{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652907"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18546"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18546"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.21,0.07,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75736"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11278"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61249"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1879"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"10869"},{"type":"tags","id":"10870"},{"type":"tags","id":"10873"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26159"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75736"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents with watery diarrhoea, abdominal cramping, and bloating for two weeks after returning from a camping trip where she drank from a mountain stream. Microscopic examination of a stool sample reveals oval-shaped cysts with four nuclei, as well as pear-shaped organisms with eight flagella.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Giardia intestinalis","Entamoeba histolytica","Cryptosporidium parvum","Cyclospora cayetanensis","Blastocystis hominis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGiardia intestinalis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of waterborne diarrhoeal illness, particularly if consumption is from untreated water sources like mountain streams. The characteristic oval cysts with four nuclei seen on stool microscopy are diagnostic. The trophozoite form has a distinctive pear-shaped body with eight flagella that aid in motility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E causes bloody diarrhoea and has cysts with up to four nuclei but they are spherical rather than oval. Its trophozoite form has pseudopods rather than flagella.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECryptosporidium parvum\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E causes similar symptoms but has small round oocysts with four sporozoites. It does not have a flagellated form.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECyclospora cayetanensis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E produces larger spherical oocysts that require special staining to visualize. No flagellated forms are seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBlastocystis hominis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E has a distinctive large vacuolated appearance unlike the oval cysts described and does not possess flagella in any of its life cycle stages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of the clinical history (drinking from mountain stream), symptoms (watery diarrhoea without blood), and characteristic microscopy findings makes \u003Cem\u003EGiardia intestinalis\u003C/em\u003E the clear diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Giardia intestinalis is a flagellated protozoan commonly acquired from drinking contaminated water.","Giardia exists in two forms: the infectious cyst form and the trophozoite form that causes disease.","Microscopic examination of stool reveals characteristic oval cysts with four nuclei and trophozoites with pear-shaped bodies and eight flagella."],"references":["Vicente B, Freitas A, Freitas M, Midlej V. Systematic Review of Diagnostic Approaches for Human Giardiasis: Unveiling Optimal Strategies. Diagnostics (Basel). 2024 Feb 7;14(4):364. Available at:  https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10887752/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61249"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18546"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61249"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T12:08:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T12:08:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11278"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75736"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synon